column8: Do you have a technical background?
column9: I successfully taught the robot how to do the task.
column10: The robot correctly updated its understanding about aspects of the task that I did want to change.
column11: The robot wrongly updated its understanding about aspects of the task I did NOT want to change.
column12: The robot understood which aspects of the task I wanted to change, and how to change them.
column14: I had to try to undo corrections that I gave to the robot, because it learned the wrong thing.
column15: Sometimes my corrections were just meant to fix the effect of previous corrections I gave.
column16: I had to re-teach the robot about an aspect of the task that it started off knowing well.
column17: When the robot learned something wrong, it was difficult for me to undo that.
column18: It was easy to re-correct the robot whenever it misunderstood a previous correction of mine.
column19: Any overall comments?
I was unsure if I was supposed to also try to keep the cup upright (as was in the "desired" trajectory) or just optimize for distance to table.
The robot learned to stay close to the table with few corrections but to make the cup upright i had to correct it several times
It was easier to teach the robot to be close to the table than to keep the cup upright. I had to make several corrections to keep the cup upright.
very responsive!
took a little longer to converge to something near optimal, but it got there eventually
second demonstration seemed to converge a lot faster and was easier to manage
definitely a stronger struggle in the beginning but faster convergence if I applied corrections more aggressively
you might consider running the experiment without explaining the two different methods; I'm sure I'm projecting some of what I know is happening
Response of the robot was somewhat unpredictable
Significantly better than ALL method for the same task, but not as convincing as ONE method for previous task
In this round I did not feel like I had to correct for any previous corrections of mine
Ended up making many more corrections this time (eg. my wanting to move it closer to the table made it switch its orientation as well)
Also had to do a series of corrections. I also noticed some discrepancy between which aspect I wanted to fix and which aspect it tried to fix

Some difficulties in teaching the robot resulted from not forseeing the effects of one type of correction on another type (trying to lower the height of the cup inadvertently changed its rotation, etc.)

At least from my perspective, it felt easier to correct the robot due to the fact that I had to worry less about how one correction would affect the other. Because I felt like I could adjust both trajectories simultaneously, it felt more manageable to guide the robot.

Maybe because I was only focusing on one correction, I noticed that the robot would seemingly follow my correction, then back off a little. In this case it seemed like it would continue to move downward momentarily after I pushed it, then would move back up a little bit.

This time I felt that the robot misinterpreted my vertical corrections (or overestimated a subtle/unintentional rotational correction) and starting rotating the cup when I didn't want it to. It was fairly straightforward to correct this.
I tried to quickly correct the orientation but the robot seems to tilt the cup again when I am correcting it.
The robot seems to change the orientation faster after my correction this time.
In the first time, the robot tilted the cup when I push it closer to the table which I was not my intention.
